Date: 0/0/1969
Source: From Forest to Farm
Author: MOORE
Vol / Page: 21
Edition:
Quote: All these stations in the mountain tussock lands would be divided by fencing into what was known as `summer' and `winter' country. The summer country was mostly comprised of the higher ranges and those lying away from the sun where the winter snowfall was heavy. Sheep were run on this range country through the summer months only, and brought down to the lower country - the winter country - in the late autumn. This consisted of rolling downs, the lower hills, and faces lying to the sun where snow did not lie.
Notes:

